  "summary": "autotel-devtools@0.1.1: keyword co-occurrence in bundled CLI/server requires human review",
  "details": "The package ships bundled CLI, server, and widget JavaScript artifacts (dist/cli.cjs, dist/cli.js, dist/index.cjs, dist/index.js, dist/server/index.{cjs,js}, dist/widget.global.js). Pattern matches fired on co-occurrence of Buffer.from(..., 'base64') decoding and the keywords 'ping' and 'POST' across these bundles. These keywords are present in the same minified outputs but their semantic context (default parameters vs hardcoded destinations, reachability at install/import vs only via explicit CLI invocation, env-var scraping vs narrow named-key handling) was not verified. The package declares a developer-tools purpose, which would plausibly include base64 token handling, HTTP POST APIs, and health-check ('ping') endpoints. No lifecycle install hooks, no attacker-controlled URL, and no credential-path read have been concretely identified in the available evidence. Routing to human review so a reviewer can de-minify the bundles and confirm whether the POST destinations are configurable/documented endpoints or hardcoded exfiltration sinks.",
